    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-12-06T16:07:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-12-06T16:07:00-05:00" n="273"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d273">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">832.2546/12–651: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Embassy in Brazil</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-12-06T16:07:00-05:00"
                            >December 6, 1951—4:07 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>540. During recent Washington visit, Admiral Alvaro Alberto<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d273fn1">President of the Brazilian National Research
                        Council.</note> discussed Brazilian interest acquiring cyclotron. He had
                    also discussed it with General Electric Co reps in Brazil and recd assurances GE
                    cld supply the cyclotron. Admiral was told that obtaining a license export
                    instrument from US to Brazil wld probably present no difficulty. Similar
                    assurances on this point were reportedly made by reps of the US Atomic Energy
                    Commission during their recent mission to Brazil.<note n="2" xml:id="d273fn2"
                        >For information on the mission, see letter by Ambassador Johnson to
                        Arneson, December 11, <hi rend="italic">infra</hi>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Conversations between officials of the <gloss target="#t_AEC1">AEC</gloss> and
                    the GE develop fact that company has not agreed manufacture the instrument and
                    is quite reluctant to do so. Reasons are that instrument is very difficult to
                    fabricate and wld require materials difficult obtain. GE has given the
                    Commission to understand that Brazilian order will be accepted only if the US
                    Govt formally requests it.</p>
                <p>What authority, if any, Commission may have in such situation not now clear and,
                    as practical matter, Commission does not wish consider applying pressure on
                    company unless benefits to the Commission from so doing are quite clear.
                    Reaction of Brazilian Govt to proposals recently made and discussed by <gloss
                        target="#t_AEC1">AEC</gloss> reps in Brazil may have some bearing on this
                    pt.</p>
                <p>Emb’s comments requested.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Webb</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
